- [x] **G4** `ui/grid_widget.py`: background priority chain `selected > conflict > peer > cage_member > fixed > is_black > base`; black cells skip value/candidate rendering.
- [x] **G5** `ui/grid_widget.py`: suppress digit input and pencil mode for `is_black=True` cells; skip selection on mouse click; skip on arrow-key navigation.
- [x] **G6** `ui/grid_widget.py`: add `_draw_edges(painter, size, cell_size, edge_thickness, pal, dash_thin: bool = False) -> None` as a pure rendering function; `_draw_board` pre-builds `edge_thickness: dict[tuple[int,int,str], bool]` (key `(r, c, "H"|"V")` — H = edge above row r, V = edge left of col c — R5 Q4), passes it to `_draw_edges`. The dict is pre-computed by private helper `_build_edge_dict(meta, size, box_rows, box_cols) -> dict[tuple[int,int,str], bool]` called from `_draw_board`, keeping `_draw_board` readable. For Jigsaw: thick where adjacent cells differ in region id. For Killer: same thick pen as box borders where cells differ in cage; thin dashed (using `pal.cage_dash_pattern`) when same cage — cage-sum labels are drawn by the existing `_draw_cage_labels` (see VQ-1 below), not by `_draw_edges`. For Standard/Str8ts: arithmetic `i % box_rows` thick-border logic (existing, now a special case). `dash_thin=True` applies `pal.cage_dash_pattern` for thin intra-cage edges; `_draw_board` passes `dash_thin=(meta.name == Variant.KILLER)`; no variant logic inside `_draw_edges` **(GQ-1, Option A)**. `_draw_cage_labels` is **retained unchanged** — G6 removes `_draw_lines` and adds `_draw_edges`/`_build_edge_dict` only; cage-sum label rendering is already complete **(VQ-1, Option A)**. All cage cells (not just the label cell) shift their candidate mini-grid rect by the cage-label height uniformly; `_draw_candidates` receives an `offset_y` parameter for this **(VQ-2, Option B)**. **Prerequisite**: D1 (`cage_dash_pattern` field in `Palette`) must land before G6.
- [x] **G7** `ui/grid_widget.py`: Str8ts peer highlight — black cells in selected row/col receive `peer_bg` tint (handled automatically by `_peer_cells`).
- [x] **G8** `ui/grid_widget.py`: **Unified variant conflict extension** (extends G3 base scan — GQ2): the `meta: VariantMetadata | None = None` parameter and the unconditional `_draw_board` call-site update are **already complete in G3**; add **(a)** Str8ts straight-invalidity detection — flag white cells whose placed value cannot be part of any valid consecutive run in its row or column straight; **(b)** Killer conflict — flag cage cells whose partial values provably exceed the cage target or leave insufficient candidates to reach it. For KenKen, cage-cell arithmetic violation is also performed inside `_all_conflict_cells` after the row/col scan, not as a separate function (R13 Q3, Option A).
- [x] **G9** Import/export text format (R8 Q10): header block (`variant`, `size`, `seed`, `difficulty`) + digit rows (`0` = empty); Jigsaw `region_layout` as 9 successive `region_layout:` header lines, each with 9 space-separated integer region IDs (e.g. `region_layout: 0 0 0 1 1 1 2 2 2`), one line per board row **(VQ-B)**; Str8ts `mask` (`.`/`B` per row joined by `/`) + `black_givens`; Killer cages use the repeating-field format — one `cage:` header line per cage: `cage: r,c r,c r,c:N` (cell coordinates space-separated as `row,col` pairs, colon before the sum `N`; e.g. `cage: 0,0 0,1 1,0:15`) (VQ4). Validate headers and digit count on import; missing `seed` defaults to 0. The **repeating-field convention** (one `cage:` or `clue:` header line per item, same field name repeated) is established here and applied to KenKen and Kakuro in their respective Extended Variant batches. (R12 Q8, Option A)

